<BaseLayout
    title="Install a Phosphor library — Guides"
    description="How to include a Phosphor library in your Qt6 CMake project: system find_package, FetchContent, and Nix."
>
    <Topbar crumb="Install a library" current="guides" />

    <main id="main" class="container guide">

        <PageHero
            title="Install a Phosphor library"
            tagline="Link phosphor-* into your Qt6 CMake project three ways."
        >
            <p class="muted">
                Every library in the suite is a standalone CMake
                package with a stable public API under
                <code>libs/phosphor-*/include/</code>.  Consumers pull
                in just the ones they need.  See the
                <a href="/libraries/">libraries index</a> for the
                catalog.
            </p>
        </PageHero>

        <nav class="guide-toc" aria-label="On this page">
            <ul>
                <li><a href="#prereqs">Prerequisites</a></li>
                <li><a href="#system">System package (find_package)</a></li>
                <li><a href="#fetch">FetchContent</a></li>
                <li><a href="#nix">Nix flake</a></li>
                <li><a href="#headers">Including headers</a></li>
            </ul>
        </nav>

        <h2 id="prereqs">Prerequisites</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>CMake 3.16 or newer.</li>
            <li>Qt 6.6+ with the modules the specific library depends on
                (<code>QtCore</code>, <code>QtGui</code>,
                <code>QtQml</code>, <code>QtQuick</code> — check the
                library's own page for its <i>Dependencies</i> list).</li>
            <li>A C++20-capable compiler (GCC 11+, Clang 14+).</li>
            <li>For Wayland-integrating libraries:
                <code>wayland-scanner</code> and the matching protocol
                headers. Distros usually ship them in
                <code>wayland-devel</code> /
                <code>wayland-dev</code>.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="system">System package (<code>find_package</code>)</h2>
        <p>
            Once the libraries ship as distribution packages, the
            normal path is <code>find_package</code>.  Each library is
            its own package — pulling one doesn't pull the rest.
        </p>
        <pre><code class="language-cmake"># FILL: replace `phosphor-zones` with whichever library you need.
# Matches the package name from the AUR / COPR / OBS build.
find_package(phosphor-zones REQUIRED)

add_executable(my-app main.cpp)
target_link_libraries(my-app PRIVATE phosphor::zones)
</code></pre>
        <p class="muted">
            The <code>phosphor::</code> namespace is consistent across
            the suite — <code>phosphor::rendering</code>,
            <code>phosphor::shell</code>, etc.
        </p>

        <h2 id="fetch">FetchContent</h2>
        <p>
            For projects that want to pin an exact upstream commit (no
            distro package dependency), use
            <code>FetchContent</code>.  One declaration per library.
        </p>
        <pre><code class="language-cmake">include(FetchContent)

FetchContent_Declare(
    phosphor-zones
    GIT_REPOSITORY https://github.com/phosphor-works/phosphor-zones
    # FILL: use a release tag once one exists.
    GIT_TAG        FILL
)
FetchContent_MakeAvailable(phosphor-zones)

target_link_libraries(my-app PRIVATE phosphor::zones)
</code></pre>

        <h2 id="nix">Nix flake</h2>
        <p>
            If you're on Nix or NixOS, the umbrella flake exposes one
            package per library under the same namespace.
        </p>
        <pre><code class="language-nix">{`# flake.nix excerpt
{
  inputs.phosphor.url = "github:phosphor-works/phosphor";
  # FILL: confirm the umbrella flake input path once the monorepo
  # split is finalized.  Individual libraries may publish their own
  # flakes instead.

  outputs = { self, nixpkgs, phosphor, ... }: {
    devShells.x86_64-linux.default = nixpkgs.legacyPackages.x86_64-linux.mkShell {
      buildInputs = [
        phosphor.packages.x86_64-linux.zones
        phosphor.packages.x86_64-linux.rendering
      ];
    };
  };
}
`}</code></pre>

        <h2 id="headers">Including headers</h2>
        <p>
            Every library exposes a single stable top-level header and
            matches the doxygen namespace shown on its library page.
            Include what you need:
        </p>
        <pre><code class="language-cpp">#include &lt;phosphor-zones/Zone.h&gt;
#include &lt;phosphor-zones/IZoneDetector.h&gt;
#include &lt;phosphor-rendering/ShaderEffect.h&gt;

// FILL: whatever the library-specific header set ends up being —
// the shape is `phosphor-&lt;slug&gt;/&lt;TypeName&gt;.h`.

using namespace PhosphorZones;

auto zone = Zone{ /* ... */ };
</code></pre>
        <p class="muted">
            The <a href="/api/">API reference</a> lists every header
            and type under its generated namespace page.
        </p>

        <SiteFooter
            note="Install guide · GPL-3.0-or-later"
